Solid enables users to select where their data is stored and who gets access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said that the intention behind Inrupt was the "world domination".
"We need to get active now," he said on the topic of startup.
"It is a historic moment."
The application uses the technology of Solid so that users can create their own personal online data storage or a POD.
It can include contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library as well as other tools for the private and business sector.
Similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all content are available in one browser and at the same time.
The special thing about the personal online data storage is that the user can only decide who can access which data.
The company describes this concept as personal enhancement and development of data.
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company uses resources, processes and corresponding skills to ensure that solid is available to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, some developers who have been hired to work on this project, as well as a community of volunteer programmers. Furthermore, a security platform purchased by IBM will be used.
With the start of this week, technology developers worldwide will be able to create their own decentralised apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee announced that he and his team will not exchange with Facebook and Google about whether a comprehensive change will be made, in which their entire business models will be completely redesigned overnight.
"We do not ask for their permission."
Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt has the task of providing commercial energy generation and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new, solid-based web.
In 1994, Berners-Lee redesigned the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has been a major participant in the debate on net neutrality.
Even with the start of Inrupt Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely confident about this new era of the web," he added.
