National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out in an estate in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape in food search.
It is hoped that the results will allow further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to guide future nature conservation activities.
The study carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will detect dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown langohr and water bats in Inverewe Garden in West Ross.
Special recorders are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
In the case of a sound analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and what species does what.
Next, a map and a report of the habitat are created to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
These data will help to determine and demonstrate the benefits of life management measures such as the creation of meadows and how forest areas for bats and other related species can be obtained.
The stocks of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to the loss of the habitat.
Windwheels and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their ears are more useful because of their nightly hunting habits than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echoing to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across Scotland, takes the topic of bats very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who carry out regular investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Governor David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for her.
"Here in Threeave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we don't yet know about bats, so here and at other goods we carry out these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of first excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it was possible that the accidental destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and eliminate the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish civil servant of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still need to learn a lot about bats and many of our species we don't know how it is about their populations."
