More than 16,000 people were evacuated in Palu after the disaster.
Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city just celebrated its 40th anniversary as the earthquake and the tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a government district extending over a coastline of over 300 km (180 miles) in the northwest of the island of Sulawesi.
In 2017, 299,200 people lived in the government district, an administrative unit below the province.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of revenue in the Central Sulawesi economy, in particular the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it focuses mainly on Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesia Civil Protection Authority, Palu and Donggala have been several victims of earthquakes and tsunamis over the last 100 years.
In 1938 over 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West Donggala was hit in 1996 by a tsunami in which nine people died.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific fire ring, and is regularly haunted by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in the north of Sumatras triggered a tsunami on 26 December, which struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, almost half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatras between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias Islands off the coast of Sumatras.
2006: An earthquake with a strength of 6.8 shook the south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 deaths.
2009: An earthquake with a strength of 7.6 hit the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with the strength 7.5 shook one of the Mentawai islands in front of Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of up to 10 meters altitude, which destroyed dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: A slight earthquake shook the government district of Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic when people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people died from a falling building.
2018: Heavy earthquakes hit the Indonesian island of Lombok popular with tourists and claimed more than 500 deaths on the north side of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and thousands of tourists were temporarily stranded on the island.
