Why Beijing could benefit from the US-China trade war
The opening ointments of the trade war between the US and China were deafening. Although the battle is not over for a long time, Beijing could benefit from a long-term grave between the countries, my experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, fired the first warning signal at the beginning of the year when he imposed fines on important Chinese exports, including solar cells, steel and aluminium.
The most important escalation took place this week with new fines on goods worth 200 billion dollars, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China to the USA.
Beijing struck back in the same way every time and recently raised fines of five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China has sworn to respond to any US measure and it is unlikely that the second largest economic power in the world will soon stumble.
Moving Washington in the way would mean giving up. However, a public squandering over the US would be far too embarrassing for China's President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays out its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a fast political decision could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries in Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized," said Abigail Grace, a scientist who focuses herself on Asia at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria would be 'ready' for the return of refugees, according to the Foreign Minister.
Syria says that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the war of over seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem declared that the circumstances in the country improve.
"Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure," he said.
The government is building up the areas destroyed by terrorists to reverse normality.
All the conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country which they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed aid in the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept any conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the Ryder Cup 2018 and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 in Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won back the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the US.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over a large part of the tournament, sank off the 16th Railway (Par 3) in the water and lost against Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the Europe Team, Thorbjorn Oles from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the English Ian Poulter who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spanish Sergio Garcia, veteran from eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all times with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
