Red Time update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red-time concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more complete flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae blossom extends over about 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Flecken can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough district, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
In the last week, average concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee district and low concentrations in Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the regions of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems have been known over the past week.
